Readiness Probe Failures

Your container is running.

The application process is up.

But Kubernetes still refuses to send traffic to the pod.

❌ Pod Not Ready

❌ Service Not Routing Traffic

❌ Deployment Rollout Stuck

This is often caused by Readiness Probe Failures.

Recently, I encountered a deployment where all pods were running, but none of them were receiving production traffic.

🔍 My troubleshooting approach:

✅ Checked pod events

✅ Reviewed readiness probe configuration

✅ Verified application health endpoint

✅ Tested health check URLs manually

✅ Checked startup time requirements

✅ Reviewed probe timing parameters

✅ Verified service connectivity

✅ Examined application logs

🎯 Root Cause:

The readiness probe was configured to start checking the application too early.

The application required additional startup time before the health endpoint became available.

As a result, Kubernetes continuously marked the pod as Not Ready.

After increasing the initialDelaySeconds value and adjusting probe timing, the readiness checks succeeded and traffic started flowing normally.

💡 Key Takeaway:

When troubleshooting Readiness Probe Failures, focus on whether the application is actually ready to serve requests.

Always verify:

• Health check endpoint

• initialDelaySeconds

• periodSeconds

• timeoutSeconds

• failureThreshold

• Application startup time

• Network connectivity

Useful commands:

kubectl describe pod <pod-name>

kubectl logs <pod-name>

kubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- curl localhost:<port>/health

Remember:

📌 Running ≠ Ready

📌 Kubernetes sends traffic only to Ready pods.

📌 Incorrect readiness probe settings can block deployments even when applications are healthy.

Every troubleshooting session improves our understanding of Kubernetes application lifecycle management and traffic routing.
